data.content:
This is the **C# 14 `Span<T>` overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions mean `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. The `MemoryExtensions` overload is **not representable in expression trees**, so when you compile with `preferInterpretation: true`, it throws at runtime (`NotSupportedException`).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

All three force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains`, which is valid in expression trees. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays and any other LINQ method that now resolves to a `Span`/`MemoryExtensions` overload.
